WEBVTT

00:49.750 --> 00:52.916
I just received confirmation.
The boys are back in Camp des Milles.

00:52.916 --> 00:53.958
Are they okay?

00:53.958 --> 00:55.208
They're alive.

00:55.208 --> 00:56.750
Well, that's a relief.

00:56.750 --> 00:59.250
You do understand that if they talk,
they'll talk about you.

01:01.458 --> 01:04.416
- No. No, they wouldn't talk about me.
If you're lucky.

01:05.208 --> 01:07.375
If Vichy learns of your involvement
from them,

01:07.875 --> 01:10.041
we will not be able to protect you.

01:10.041 --> 01:13.125
If pressed, we will deny
any knowledge of your activities.

01:13.833 --> 01:15.375
How? I live with Thomas.

01:15.375 --> 01:17.250
The Villa Air-Bel is a big house.

01:17.250 --> 01:19.958
How should he know
what any of his tenants do all day?

01:20.458 --> 01:21.500
Thomas.

01:22.833 --> 01:24.166
Thomas!

01:26.875 --> 01:28.125
Look, it's not up to me.

01:29.458 --> 01:31.083
We're all following orders.

01:34.291 --> 01:35.333
Who are you?

01:36.166 --> 01:37.541
Now you're asking me questions?

01:37.541 --> 01:40.541
Who are you? Where do you go
when you leave these meetings?

01:40.541 --> 01:43.750
What about you?
Is Lovegrove even a real name?

01:43.750 --> 01:44.708
Don't.

01:44.708 --> 01:48.875
No! You two can pretend
like you don't know anything about me,

01:48.875 --> 01:53.083
but I am an open book!
It's me that knows nothing about you!

01:53.083 --> 01:55.916
This war is bigger than any one of us,
Mary Jayne.

01:55.916 --> 01:57.875
The Nazis are flattening Manchester.

01:57.875 --> 02:00.041
We need to get those men out
before Christmas.

02:00.541 --> 02:01.916
You must make that happen.

02:01.916 --> 02:03.083
On my own?

02:03.083 --> 02:04.041
Margaux.

02:04.833 --> 02:05.875
I'll go with her.

02:07.166 --> 02:09.000
Let her go on her own.

02:09.000 --> 02:10.583
Oh, because I'm dispensable.

02:10.583 --> 02:14.375
- Because it's your fault they're in there.
- So why should I do this for you?

02:14.375 --> 02:15.750
Because if you don't,

02:15.750 --> 02:19.291
we will withdraw our financial support
from the Emergency Rescue Committee.

02:58.708 --> 03:00.083
Good morning.

03:01.041 --> 03:02.666
What's wrong with me?

03:03.458 --> 03:04.833
Absolutely nothing.

03:07.416 --> 03:08.833
I'm sleeping too well.

03:10.916 --> 03:12.083
That is a good thing.

03:12.833 --> 03:15.625
Everyone at the villa is
waiting to get out of here.

03:16.583 --> 03:18.291
Every day, they ask me when.

03:18.833 --> 03:21.291
Have your nosy roommates figured out
what we are doing?

03:21.958 --> 03:22.958
Does it matter?

03:23.833 --> 03:25.625
It would to some people.

03:25.625 --> 03:28.416
Well, we don't care about those people,
do we?

03:31.041 --> 03:32.666
- We don't care.
- We don't.

03:55.291 --> 03:58.083
<i>Hannah Arendt is always up
at the crack of dawn.</i>

03:59.666 --> 04:02.458
We were in the internment camp
at Gurs together

04:03.625 --> 04:05.500
when the Germans invaded Paris.

04:06.666 --> 04:08.416
It was complete chaos.

04:10.083 --> 04:13.875
The French guards abandoned their posts
and left the gates wide open.

04:18.458 --> 04:19.750
But I couldn't leave.

04:21.500 --> 04:22.416
I was

04:23.416 --> 04:24.625
paralyzed with fear.

04:28.166 --> 04:29.208
Hannah...

04:30.291 --> 04:32.583
Hannah just stood up and walked out,

04:32.583 --> 04:34.875
like it was
the simplest thing in the world.

04:36.708 --> 04:38.583
She gave me the courage to leave too.

04:40.791 --> 04:44.375
If only I could return the favor now
and get her out of here.

04:51.041 --> 04:52.166
Good morning.

05:06.333 --> 05:07.791
Sorry, Ms. Arendt.

05:09.916 --> 05:12.208
Oh, no, just your... mm...

05:13.041 --> 05:14.250
language.

05:14.250 --> 05:16.541
Sorry. My English...

05:16.541 --> 05:17.958
You know, actually...

05:20.666 --> 05:24.208
I learned a bit of German in Berlin.

05:25.291 --> 05:26.208
Oh.

05:26.208 --> 05:27.541
What are you doing there?

05:29.833 --> 05:33.541
Translating my friend
Walter Benjamin's work into English,

05:33.541 --> 05:36.458
It's a good way to teach myself English.

05:36.458 --> 05:40.125
America will be indebted to you.

05:40.125 --> 05:44.083
Then please tell America
to give me a visa.

05:46.541 --> 05:50.458
Unfortunately, I can't help you with that.

05:53.125 --> 05:54.541
Because I am not on your list?

06:12.541 --> 06:14.541
Varian.
I'm in a hurry.

06:16.125 --> 06:19.583
We should celebrate Christmas here.
Raise people's spirits.

06:20.416 --> 06:21.333
What do you think?

06:21.833 --> 06:24.916
- We could decorate that tree.
- I thought Jews didn't celebrate.

06:24.916 --> 06:27.250
We're in Europe.
Everybody celebrates Christmas.

06:29.416 --> 06:32.750
Varian! Please, talk to me.

06:35.416 --> 06:36.250
No.

06:48.541 --> 06:51.041
Okay.
Okay, I'll leave it.

06:51.041 --> 06:52.625
Some quiet?
Okay.

06:52.625 --> 06:54.000
- Easy.
Yes.

06:54.000 --> 06:56.375
No worries.
- Silence is nice.

06:58.500 --> 07:00.791
- Good morning.
- Good morning. Um...

07:02.125 --> 07:04.041
I need to speak with you.

07:05.250 --> 07:06.375
I was just leaving.

07:06.375 --> 07:08.583
You too, as well, please.

07:10.958 --> 07:11.791
Have a seat.

07:28.458 --> 07:33.458
I need to break the British POWs out
of the prison camp.

07:33.458 --> 07:36.541
Of course you do.
Please.

07:38.750 --> 07:42.041
Even if this were possible,
how do you know they're in there?

07:42.041 --> 07:46.375
Well, me, I know nothing,
but I trust my source.

07:46.375 --> 07:49.916
- This is a British intelligence officer?
- Special operations executive.

07:49.916 --> 07:51.500
She goes by the name of Margaux.

07:51.500 --> 07:53.500
- And Lovegrove?
- He works for her.

07:53.500 --> 07:54.458
Ah, I knew it.

07:57.041 --> 07:57.958
I want to meet her.

07:57.958 --> 08:00.791
You help me with this,
and I will arrange the introduction.

08:01.750 --> 08:02.666
Please?

08:02.666 --> 08:04.375
I cannot do this on my own.

08:07.125 --> 08:10.041
We can't just head in there
without knowing how to get out.

08:10.041 --> 08:11.625
Bellmer was inside.

08:11.625 --> 08:13.041
The artist?

08:13.041 --> 08:16.500
He's at the villa.
- That's right. I could talk to him. Yes.

08:20.875 --> 08:21.916
Please.

08:27.000 --> 08:29.625
I will need to check out
the perimeter of the prison yard.

08:31.875 --> 08:33.750
- Good morning.

08:34.500 --> 08:35.500
Morning.

08:36.666 --> 08:39.416
Morning.
We'll be with you as soon as we can.

08:40.541 --> 08:41.958
- Good morning.
- Morning.

08:41.958 --> 08:43.791
I was thinking.
- Varian--

08:43.791 --> 08:47.458
We should rework the interview to account
for all possible paths to entry.

08:47.458 --> 08:49.750
Some people might be able
to get into the United States

08:49.750 --> 08:51.416
as a student, for example.

08:52.541 --> 08:54.666
Good morning.
Are you here for an interview?

08:54.666 --> 08:58.375
I'm Dillon Reese, Mr. Fry.
I'm from the American consulate.

08:59.000 --> 09:00.541
- I'm sorry?
- I was trying to tell you.

09:00.541 --> 09:03.333
- I'm your replacement.
- My replacement?

09:03.833 --> 09:06.500
You've been fired, but you know that.

09:06.500 --> 09:09.208
- Don't be ridiculous!
- I wanted to give you this.

09:22.958 --> 09:27.208
- Twenty-four hours to leave the country?
- It's all clearly explained in the letter.

09:27.208 --> 09:30.833
Your French work visa was terminated
with your employment.

09:32.541 --> 09:36.625
Don't you worry. I'm gonna keep this place
running like a Swiss clock.

09:39.125 --> 09:41.916
- Have you called Bingham?
- Yes, he was completely in the dark.

09:42.416 --> 09:45.916
- Varian, you can't let this happen.
- I won't. I'm gonna fight this until--

09:45.916 --> 09:47.666
Simmer down.

09:49.208 --> 09:50.500
What did you just say to me?

09:50.500 --> 09:53.875
We're all adults here, Mr. Fry.
Everything's gonna be fine.

10:04.458 --> 10:06.791
- Please don't tell anyone about this.
- Mm-hmm.

10:07.375 --> 10:08.208
I will be back.

10:08.875 --> 10:10.250
Have a pleasant day.

10:17.166 --> 10:18.125
I'm very sorry.

10:19.291 --> 10:20.416
I'll be back.

10:20.916 --> 10:22.958
I'm very sorry. I'm very sorry.

10:27.541 --> 10:28.791
I have to see him.

10:28.791 --> 10:30.000
But--
- Now!

10:30.000 --> 10:31.291
Uh... N...

10:33.000 --> 10:33.916
Next Wednesday.

10:33.916 --> 10:36.500
Next Wednesday? No, that is much too late.

10:41.833 --> 10:42.958
What a pity!

11:07.750 --> 11:08.750
Patterson?

11:10.541 --> 11:11.375
Patterson!

11:12.958 --> 11:14.166
You can't do this.

11:14.166 --> 11:17.291
Please, Mr. Fry,
you give me far too much credit.

11:17.291 --> 11:20.250
I'm just a bureaucrat
following orders from on high.

11:20.250 --> 11:22.000
What did you say to them?

11:23.541 --> 11:24.958
About you?
- Yes!

11:27.125 --> 11:28.166
Only the truth.

12:09.833 --> 12:11.083
Mr. Bellmer?

12:13.916 --> 12:14.791
Uh...

12:14.791 --> 12:16.958
May I ask you an, um...

12:17.833 --> 12:19.583
an unusual question?

12:23.125 --> 12:26.333
Do you remember anything
about the inside of Camp des Milles?

12:42.333 --> 12:45.250
I remember <i>everything</i>
about Camp des Milles.

12:46.375 --> 12:50.166
I will never forget one inch
of that place for as long as I live.

12:53.250 --> 12:57.000
The feeling of other people
pressed up against me day and night.

12:57.750 --> 12:59.750
Their warm, wet bodies.

13:01.458 --> 13:03.208
The stench of humanity.

13:08.458 --> 13:10.958
Do you think that you could build me

13:10.958 --> 13:13.458
a model of the inside of the camp

13:13.958 --> 13:16.250
and the outside of the camp?

13:18.541 --> 13:19.625
Why?

13:19.625 --> 13:22.000
Because I wanna help other men escape.

13:24.333 --> 13:25.333
Then of course.

14:43.500 --> 14:46.875
You can meet here
any time you like. It's safe here.

14:54.166 --> 14:55.166
Thank you.

15:15.333 --> 15:16.291
<i>Gentlemen.</i>

15:17.708 --> 15:19.708
We are playing the long game here.

15:20.291 --> 15:22.541
Once we've driven
the Germans out of France,

15:23.375 --> 15:25.208
we will drive the French out of Africa!

15:25.708 --> 15:27.791
So why is
a white man joining our conversation?

15:28.791 --> 15:30.000
Um...

15:31.083 --> 15:32.125
I'm a Jew.

15:32.125 --> 15:33.750
You're still white.

15:33.750 --> 15:36.666
Albert has as much at stake here
as any of us do.

15:38.958 --> 15:40.000
Gentlemen.

15:41.083 --> 15:42.166
Gentlemen.

15:43.416 --> 15:44.791
We need allies.

15:46.000 --> 15:47.416
We also need weapons.

15:47.416 --> 15:49.166
Training. Intelligence.

15:50.916 --> 15:52.166
Where from?

15:53.750 --> 15:55.000
To start? From the British.

15:58.250 --> 15:59.083
The British?

16:00.000 --> 16:02.208
They have
the largest colonial empire in the world!

16:02.208 --> 16:05.083
But right here, right now,
they share our goals.

16:06.250 --> 16:08.458
If we break their POWs out tomorrow,

16:08.958 --> 16:11.083
we'll cement the collaboration
going forward.

16:15.625 --> 16:16.625
Who's in?

16:36.250 --> 16:39.833
Here's the list of current inmates.

16:40.958 --> 16:42.833
The men you're looking for are on it.

16:43.583 --> 16:45.916
I can tip them off
so they know you're coming.

16:45.916 --> 16:48.500
But you must be prepared to move quickly.

16:51.166 --> 16:52.916
We protect the perimeter of the camp.

16:53.500 --> 16:56.958
We shoot to kill. That's the job.

17:00.875 --> 17:02.916
Realistically, we can
only hold our fire for, what,

17:05.500 --> 17:07.250
maybe 60 seconds maximum?

17:10.166 --> 17:13.333
If the French guards think
that we're allowing prisoners to escape,

17:14.250 --> 17:15.250
believe me,

17:16.416 --> 17:17.583
they'll shoot us.

17:23.250 --> 17:28.083
I have some good news
and some... better news.

17:28.083 --> 17:31.750
- Where should I start?
- You know, I miss Americans. Go on.

17:32.458 --> 17:34.916
The good news is that we've been having

17:34.916 --> 17:39.500
some very eager conversations
with our European customers.

17:39.500 --> 17:40.750
Cheers to that.

17:40.750 --> 17:46.333
ACM's goal, no matter what
the result of this blasted war, is simple.

17:46.958 --> 17:50.500
We wanna see American business
thrive in the region.

17:50.500 --> 17:52.958
Well, how else
can we exert democratic influence?

17:52.958 --> 17:55.541
We have to preserve
our ability to work with both sides.

17:55.541 --> 17:56.583
That's right.

17:57.083 --> 18:01.291
Roosevelt declares war, well,
he'll be forfeiting our seat at the table.

18:01.291 --> 18:03.083
I couldn't agree with you more.

18:03.583 --> 18:06.208
Which brings me to the better news.

18:06.958 --> 18:10.125
ACM would like
to officially offer you a job.

18:12.458 --> 18:13.291
Me?

18:13.916 --> 18:15.791
Let me know if I'm out of line here,

18:15.791 --> 18:18.875
but we need someone
to be our man in Europe,

18:19.791 --> 18:22.291
and I can think of no one better than you.

18:22.791 --> 18:26.625
That is, if and when you're ready
to move into the private sector.

18:34.541 --> 18:36.541
Well, as it happens,

18:37.208 --> 18:39.458
I'm entitled to retire
from the Foreign Service

18:39.458 --> 18:41.250
when I turn 50 this spring.

18:57.875 --> 18:58.750
Varian.

19:03.875 --> 19:05.125
Why are you so angry?

19:06.375 --> 19:10.958
Which of the many laws that I've broken
offends you the most? Fighting fascism?

19:14.125 --> 19:15.291
Harboring radicals?

19:16.291 --> 19:18.000
- Loving men?
- Stop.

19:18.000 --> 19:21.333
If I have to live a life where
everything worth fighting for is illegal

19:21.333 --> 19:23.416
and everything worth doing is a crime,

19:25.041 --> 19:26.541
then call me a criminal.

19:28.958 --> 19:30.250
I won't apologize for that.

19:30.250 --> 19:33.166
You lied to me
about who you're working for.

19:33.166 --> 19:35.625
By omission. For a reason.

19:35.625 --> 19:38.750
And in doing so,
you have threatened my entire operation.

19:39.500 --> 19:42.833
It's only a matter of time before
the French discover I'm operating out of--

19:42.833 --> 19:45.000
What? A British spy nest!

19:45.875 --> 19:48.583
And when the Americans find out,
I'm gonna get it from both sides.

19:48.583 --> 19:51.416
What I should do is
I should leave this house

19:52.000 --> 19:55.125
and take everyone in it with me.
But where would we go, Thomas?

19:56.166 --> 19:57.541
There's nowhere to go!

20:05.666 --> 20:07.416
Why are you working for the British?

20:12.125 --> 20:15.041
Because they're the only ones
fighting the Nazis.

20:17.708 --> 20:19.666
Winston Churchill is a friend of the Jews.

20:19.666 --> 20:23.250
Winston Churchill is a virulent
anti-Semite behind closed doors.

20:23.250 --> 20:25.708
I don't care what he does
behind closed doors.

20:25.708 --> 20:28.291
I actually don't care what anyone does
behind closed doors.

20:30.583 --> 20:33.250
Churchill's promised
to deliver us a homeland.

20:35.958 --> 20:36.958
And we need one.

20:57.958 --> 20:58.791
Hannah.

21:03.333 --> 21:04.750
I really can't help you.

21:07.625 --> 21:10.708
Lost my job,
and I've been kicked out of France.

21:11.833 --> 21:13.333
But you still have rights.

21:14.375 --> 21:15.541
American rights!

21:15.541 --> 21:17.166
But I'm in France.

21:17.166 --> 21:19.666
We are all in France, Mr. Fry.

21:20.458 --> 21:21.291
Yeah.

21:21.291 --> 21:24.500
As an American, you have
the right to stay here as a tourist.

21:24.500 --> 21:25.791
I don't.

21:25.791 --> 21:28.541
I am probably
the most German person you know.

21:29.708 --> 21:31.541
I miss everything about my home country.

21:32.375 --> 21:33.375
The language,

21:34.125 --> 21:35.208
the poetry,

21:35.791 --> 21:36.875
even the weather.

21:39.041 --> 21:41.875
But I am no longer a German citizen.
You see?

21:42.791 --> 21:43.791
No rights.

21:48.333 --> 21:50.125
You must be terribly homesick.

21:50.750 --> 21:51.916
Homesick?

21:53.125 --> 21:55.416
Homeless, Mr. Fry.

21:57.708 --> 21:59.041
I'm stateless.

22:02.208 --> 22:03.833
The only entrance is here.

22:06.125 --> 22:11.083
The barbed wire here is weak
in some places and thin enough to be cut.

22:12.541 --> 22:15.708
When I was there,
some boys were trying to tunnel out here.

22:16.208 --> 22:18.291
It all comes down
to getting the soldiers

22:18.291 --> 22:20.083
to the right place at the right time.

22:20.083 --> 22:22.541
I'm sure they've fixed it.
Maybe, maybe not.

22:22.541 --> 22:23.791
At least it's possible.

22:23.791 --> 22:25.875
Touré has a sharpshooter uniform for me.

22:25.875 --> 22:29.250
You distract the guards at the front.
I will slip inside to find the men.

22:29.250 --> 22:31.916
Then we meet you around here,
the barbed wire.

22:31.916 --> 22:34.625
- Mm-hmm.
- And if you get stuck inside?

22:37.125 --> 22:38.041
I won't.

22:40.875 --> 22:42.916
Touré told the prisoners
to expect us tonight.

22:42.916 --> 22:44.000
Good.

22:45.833 --> 22:47.458
Do you know Hans Fittko?

22:48.750 --> 22:49.666
What?

22:50.166 --> 22:52.541
Do you know someone
whose name is Hans Fittko?

22:53.500 --> 22:56.041
This is the list
of current prisoners in Camp des Milles.

23:03.125 --> 23:04.125
But he's dead.

23:08.208 --> 23:09.583
What's going on?

23:09.583 --> 23:13.083
There’s a man named Hans Fittko
at Des Milles with the British prisoners.

23:14.625 --> 23:15.750
Your brother?

23:19.750 --> 23:20.958
My husband.

23:21.916 --> 23:23.208
What?

23:23.208 --> 23:24.541
You're married?

23:26.333 --> 23:27.541
This can't be right.

23:28.875 --> 23:32.333
But what if it is?
If it is, then we have to get him out.

23:32.833 --> 23:35.291
Please, let me do this for you.

23:35.291 --> 23:37.250
Please, because I owe you.

23:39.666 --> 23:40.625
- Yes.

23:40.625 --> 23:43.000
Yes.
- Mary Jayne, don't do this.

23:44.291 --> 23:45.625
This is not your concern.

23:45.625 --> 23:49.625
Drop me off at the front gate.
I'm gonna use Dagobert as a distraction.

23:49.625 --> 23:50.958
Your dog?

23:50.958 --> 23:54.833
This is my mission, and I'm gonna run it
how I see fit. Do you drive?

23:54.833 --> 23:57.250
- Mary Jayne.
- I thought I was on my own.

24:08.625 --> 24:09.708
Um...

24:11.875 --> 24:15.541
We need to show Lisa's husband
something familiar or he won't trust us.

24:19.041 --> 24:20.333
You must have something.

24:22.666 --> 24:23.666
One thing.

24:25.416 --> 24:26.791
My wedding ring.

24:28.875 --> 24:29.875
Bring it to me.

24:31.625 --> 24:32.541
Paul...

24:36.541 --> 24:38.250
I thought he was dead.

24:42.625 --> 24:43.750
War is complicated.

24:45.458 --> 24:46.416
He's a good man.

24:48.750 --> 24:49.833
Just get the ring.

24:50.708 --> 24:51.625
Please.

25:09.625 --> 25:10.833
Thank you, sir.

25:12.166 --> 25:14.416
Tourist visas? Number 134.

25:14.416 --> 25:15.333
Yes.

25:20.958 --> 25:21.791
Three months.

25:22.541 --> 25:25.041
I just need your local address.
Is this it?

25:25.041 --> 25:26.041
Yes.

25:26.791 --> 25:27.875
Is it a hotel?

25:27.875 --> 25:30.666
No. A private residence.

25:30.666 --> 25:33.916
Ah. Then we need the signature
of your landlord. One moment.

25:33.916 --> 25:35.375
Sir, excuse me--

25:53.375 --> 25:55.500
Villa Air-Bel. 63 Avenue Jean Lombard?

25:55.500 --> 25:59.416
Yes. Why is this necessary?
The landlord is Thomas Lovegrove.

26:00.333 --> 26:04.541
But it says here that the house belongs to
a certain Mrs. Marguerite Nouget.

